<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Calocedrus</i> <i>decurrens</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>ponderosa</i> and/or <i>Pseudotsuga</i> <i>menziesii</i> are co-dominant in the tree canopy with <i>Abies</i> <i>concolor</i>, <i>Alnus</i> <i>rhombifolia</i>, <i>Arbutus</i> <i>menziesii</i>, <i>Calocedrus</i> <i>decurrens</i>, <i>Notholithocarpus</i> <i>densiflorus</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>coulteri</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>jeffreyi</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>lambertiana</i>, <i>Pseudotsuga</i> <i>macrocarpa</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>chrysolepis</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>garryana</i> or <i>Quercus</i> <i>kelloggii</i>. Associated shrubs include <i>Amelanchier</i> <i>utahensis</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> spp., <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>prostratus</i>, <i>Chamaebatia</i> <i>foliolosa</i>, <i>Mahonia</i> <i>nervosa</i>, <i>Purshia</i> <i>tridentata</i> and <i>Quercus</i> <i>vacciniifolia</i>. Associated herbs include <i>Achnatherum</i> <i>occidentale</i>, <i>Antennaria</i> <i>rosea</i>, <i>Balsamorhiza</i> <i>sagittata</i>, <i>Collinsia</i> <i>parviflora</i>, <i>Elymus</i> <i>elymoides</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>nudum</i>, <i>Galium</i> <i>bolanderi</i>, <i>Poa</i> <i>secunda</i>, <i>Polygala</i> <i>cornuta</i>, <i>Polystichum</i> <i>munitum</i> and <i>Wyethia</i> <i>mollis</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text"> Trees < 75 m; canopy is continuous or intermittent. Shrub layer is sparse to intermittent. Herbaceous layer is sparse to abundant. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Pinus ponderosa</i>, <i>Calocedrus decurrens</i>, and/or <i>Pseudotsuga menziesii</i> are dominant or co-dominant and together comprise  >60% relative cover in the tree canopy (Ratchford et al. 2022a, 2021b).</li>
		
		<li>Both <i>Pinus ponderosa</i> and <i>Calocedrus decurrens</i> > 1% absolute cover in tree canopy and/or in the regeneration layers; combined, they comprise > 60% relative cover in the tree canopy (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b).</li>
		
		<li><i>Pseudotsuga menziesii</i> and <i>Pinus ponderosa</i> both > 30% relative cover in the canopy (Bingham 1999).</li>
		
		<li><i>Calocedrus decurrens</i> is >30% relative cover in the tree layer with <i>Pinus ponderosa</i> (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
		
		<li>Canopy layer comprised of at least 2 (usually 3) conifer species and 2 or more species are regenerating, including <i>Pinus ponderosa</i>, <i>Calocedrus decurrens</i>, and/or <i>Pseudotsuga menziesii</i> (Fites 1993).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Raised stream benches, terraces, slopes, and ridges of all aspects. Soils are deep and well drained. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (2012 national list) recognizes <i>Pinus ponderosa</i> and <i>Pseudotsuga menziesii</i> as FACU plants. </div>
</div>

        
