<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pinus ponderosa </i>is a large conifer that attains a height of at least 50 m and an age of 600 years. Seed production varies geographically and temporally with high seed production every 2-7 years. Plants are shade intolerant. Seedling establishment is erratic and linked to periods of adequate soil moisture, high seed crop, and the availability of partially shaded mineral soil. It is best on light soils where extensive root proliferation is possible. The presence of grasses and shrubs reduces seedling survival (Critchfield 1984, Griffin and Critchfield 1972, Habeck 1992d, Oliver and Ryker 1990). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Calocedrus decurrens </i>is a conifer that attains a height of 50 m and an age of over 500 years. Seed crops vary in 3- to 6-year cycles, with seed production lacking in some years. Seeds are wind dispersed. Germination is best under partial shade on fresh mineral soil or very light litter. Established seedlings are both shade and drought tolerant, and plants grow rapidly when released. The species grows on a wide variety of parent materials. Plants can extract soil phosphorus and calcium and exclude surplus magnesium, allowing them to grow on ultramafic substrates. Trees grow fastest on deep, well-drained, productive sites, but they commonly occur on unproductive ones as well (Habeck 1992a, Powers and Oliver 1990). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Pseudotsuga menziesii </i>is a conifer that attains at least 75 m in height and 500 years in age. Trees begin bearing cones by 20 years of age. Seed production is cyclic, with heavy crops every 5-7 years. Wind and gravity disperse seeds; most fall within 100 m of the parent tree. Seedling establishment is best on mineral soil or on light, moist litter. First-year seedlings survive and grow best in partial shade especially on drier sites, where seedling survival and growth is best in 50 percent shade. Understory trees cannot survive in dense shade, but they are more shade tolerant on moist sites than on dry ones (Barbour et al. 2007a, Griffin and Critchfield 1972, Hermann and Lavender 1990, Uchytil 1991d).<br/>
<br/>
Stands of this alliance consist of a mixed conifer canopy with codominance of at least two of the three nominal species. This is a classic mixed conifer type of the lower to mid-montane zones of California. Other conifers are also often present including <i>Pinus lambertiana, P. jeffreyi,</i> and/or <i>P. attenuata</i>. <i>Abies concolor</i> is usually lacking or at very low cover in the upper canopy. However, with long periods of fire suppression <i>A. concolor</i> may increase in the understory.<br/>
<br/>
Bingham (1999) developed a regionwide alliance-level classification for late-seral-stage forests based on relationships between species composition and major environmental gradients. This analysis led to  separating <i>Pinus ponderosa -</i> mixed conifer stands into <i>Pinus ponderosa - Calocedrus decurrens </i>alliance and <i>Pinus ponderosa - Pseudotsuga menziesii </i>alliance in the 2009 book, <i>A Manual of California Vegetation, second edition</i>. However, these two previously described alliances have been merged into one alliance based on more recent classification analyses and surveys while standardizing California vegetation names with that of the National Vegetation Classification. Although <i>Ps. menziesii</i> tends to more often codominate in the northern regions of the alliance range while <i>C. decurrens</i> codominates more in the southern regions, we found that there is significant floristic and environmental overlap between the two previously described alliances warranting a merger of the two, particularly since all three nominate species can co-dominate. Additionally, this broader mixed-conifer alliance concept is still being kept separate from the narrower <i>Pseudotsuga menziesii - Calocedrus decurrens </i>(serpentine) alliance, yet more statewide analysis will determine whether these should remain separate. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
