<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">The <i> Pinus ponderosa - Calocedrus decurrens - Pseudotsuga menziesii </i>alliance is characteristic of the warmer, lower mixed conifer zone, where snow accumulates for short periods in the winter, and where fire cycles tend to favor regeneration of these principal tree species. Stands experience a range of fires with short to moderate intervals and low to moderate intensities. Historically, surface fires and drought were influential in maintaining stands with open canopies (Skinner et al. 2006, Skinner and Taylor 2006, van Wagtendonk and Fites-Kaufman 2006). Moderate- to high-severity surface fires damage trunks, however, making trees susceptible to rots and root disease (Habeck 1992a, Powers and Oliver 1990). The ability of these principal tree species to survive fire increases with age: mature trees have thick bark and crown architecture that is more resistant, protecting them from low- to moderate-severity fires. Underburning allows older trees to survive repeated fires (Habeck 1992d, Uchytil 1991d).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
