    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ac, Ae, Ag-o, Aq-r, At-u). Stands of this alliance exist at montane elevations in the eastern subsections (Sawyer 2007). Stands characterized by <i>Pinus ponderosa</i> with <i>Pseudotsuga menziesii</i> are extensive in the southeastern subsections east of the contiguous range of <i>Notholithocarpus densiflorus</i> at mid elevations (Sawyer 2007). Stands described for the Smokey Creek RNA (Taylor and Teare 1979a, see Cheng 2004) and generally for the Six Rivers National Forest (Jimerson 1993) represent the associations in the western subsections. Some stands identified as mixed conifer forest in this section may be of other alliances (<i>Abies concolor-Pseudotsuga menziesii, Pseudotsuga menziesii-(Notholithocarpus densiflorus-Arbutus menziesii)</i>  alliances).</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gb-d, Gg-l, Gp). Stands of <i>Pinus ponderosa - Calocedrus decurrens / Ceanothus prostratus</i> Association were sampled in the Modoc Plateau subsections (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Am). Thorne et al. (2004) mapped 3800 ha in Napa Co.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba-b, Be-f). Stands characterized by <i>Pinus ponderosa</i> with <i>Pseudotsuga menziesii</i> are extensive east of the contiguous range of <i>Notholithocarpus densiflorus</i> at low and montane elevations in the section (Sawyer 2007). Stands characterized by <i>Pinus ponderosa</i> with <i> Calocedrus decurrens </i> have not been documented for this section. Some stands identified as mixed conifer forest in this section may be of other alliances (<i>Abies concolor-Pseudotsuga menziesii, Pseudotsuga menziesii-(Notholithocarpus densiflorus-Arbutus menziesii)</i> alliances).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea-h, Ej, Em, Eo-q, Es, Eu). Stands exist at montane elevations (Fites 1993, Fites-Kaufman et al. 2007, Gray 1978) throughout the section. Stands characterized by <i>Pinus ponderosa</i>  and <i>Calocedrus decurrens</i> have been found in Sugar Pine Point RNA (Palmer 1981, see Cheng 2004), in Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b), Sequoia and Kings Canyon National Parks (NPS-SEKI 2009) and generally for the Lassen, Plumas, and Eldorado national forests (Fites 1993). Stands characterized by <i>Pinus ponderosa</i>  and <i>Pseudotsuga menziesii</i> are more common in the northern subsections but can be found as far south as Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-c). Stands occur at the upper elevations of the section as far south as Lake Isabella (Menke et al. 2011, Ratchford et al. 2021a). Stands characterized by <i>Pinus ponderosa</i> and <i>Pseudotsuga menziesii</i> occur on mesic lower slopes and in canyons in the volcanic portions of the northern subsection (Menke et al. 2011).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba, Bd-e, Bg-h, Bm, Bo). Stands at montane and subalpine elevations lack <i>Pseudotsuga menziesii</i>; instead, <i>Ps. macrocarpa, Pinus coulteri,</i> and <i>P. jeffreyi</i> are part of the mixture at Big Pine Mountain RNA and at Falls Canyon and Hall Canyon RNAs (Cheng 2004, also see Minnich 2007, Minnich and Everett 2001).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Dd, Df-h, Dj, Dl-m). Stands mix with those of other mixed conifer alliances at montane elevations (Fites-Kaufman et al. 2007, Smith 1994). Stands occur at Cub Creek RNA at montane elevations(Taylor and Randall 1978, see Cheng 2004).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Fire was an integral part of the ecology of many stands of this alliance before the intensive livestock grazing of the late 1800s. Most experienced low-severity surface fires at intervals ranging from 1 to 30 years. Underburning allowed maturing trees to survive repeated fires. Since the arrival of effective fire exclusion, there has been a fuel buildup, an increase in stem density, and a change in composition toward more shade-tolerant species <i>Abies concolor, Calocedrus decurrens, </i>and <i>Pseudotsuga menziesii</i>. Additionally, early logging practices selectively removed the large pines, encouraging stands to change in composition toward shade-tolerant species (Skinner et al. 2006, Skinner and Taylor 2007). Many stands continue to experience livestock grazing, which tends to reduce grass cover and favors shrub and tree establishment (Habeck 1992a, Oliver and Ryker 1990, Schmid 1988, van Wagtendonk and Fites-Kaufman 2006). </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
